description:
File: rust/lichen-node/src/forward_buffer.rs:163,178

The dequeue and dequeue_for_source functions use swap_remove which changes the order of remaining entries:

```rust
pub fn dequeue(&mut self, now_ms: u32) -> Option<ForwardEntry> {
    // ...
    Some(self.entries.swap_remove(best_idx))  // Swaps last element to best_idx
}

pub fn dequeue_for_source(&mut self, source_iid: &[u8; 8], now_ms: u32) -> Option<ForwardEntry> {
    // ...
    Some(self.entries.swap_remove(idx))  // Swaps last element to idx
}
```

Impact: After dequeue, the packet that was at the end of entries moves to the dequeued slot. This affects iteration order for subsequent dequeue calls when there are multiple packets with the same priority/timestamp. Could cause out-of-order delivery in edge cases.

Fix: Use remove() instead of swap_remove() for O(n) stable removal, or document the unstable ordering behavior.
